CRYPTO 93 Program

Monday August 23

8:30 - 8:45  Welcome and opening remarks

Session 1:  Cryptosystems (Chair: Scott Vanstone)

8:45 - 9:05  Efficient signature schemes based on birational permutations,
Adi Shamir (Weizmann Institute of Science, Israel)

9:10 - 9:30  A new identification scheme based on syndrome decoding,
Jacques Stern (Ecole Normale Superieure, France) 

9:35 - 9:55  The shrinking generator, Don Coppersmith, Hugo Krawczyk, and 
Yishay Mansour (IBM T. J. Watson Research Center, USA)
_______________________________________________________________________

10:00 - 10:30  Break
_______________________________________________________________________

Session 2:  Cryptographic Standards (Chair: Ernie Brickell)

10:30 - 11:05  A status report on the federal government key escrow system 
(Invited talk), Miles Smid (National Institute of Standards and Technology, 
USA)
_______________________________________________________________________

Session 3:  Stream Ciphers and Cryptographic Functions (Chair: Rainer Rueppel)

11:10 - 11:30  An integrity check value algorithm for stream ciphers,
Richard Taylor (Telecom Australia Research Laboratories, Australia)

11:35 - 11:55  Nonlinearly balanced boolean functions and their propogation 
characteristics, Jennifer Seberry, Xian-Mo Zhang and Yuliang Zheng 
(University of Wollongong, Australia)
_______________________________________________________________________

Session 4:  Proof systems and Zero-knowledge (Chair: Joan Feigenbaum)

1:30 - 1:50  A low communication competitive interactive proof 
system for promised quadratic residuosity, Toshiya Itoh, Masafumi Hoshi 
and Shigeo Tsujii (Tokyo Institute of Technology, Japan)

1:55 - 2:15  Secret sharing and perfect zero knowledge, Alfredo De Santis, 
Giovanni Di Crescenzo (Universita di Salerno, Italy) and Giuseppe Persiano 
(Harvard University, USA and Universita di Catania, Italy)

2:20 - 2:40  One message proof systems with known space verifiers,
Yonaton Aumann and Uriel Feige (Weizmann Institute of Science, Israel)

2:45 - 3:05  Interactive hashing can simplify zero-knowledge protocol 
design without complexity assumptions, Ivan Damgard (University of Aarhus, 
Denmark)
_______________________________________________________________________

3:10 - 3:40  Break
_______________________________________________________________________

Session 5:  Secret Sharing (Chair: Mihir Bellare)

3:40 - 4:00  Fully dynamic secret sharing schemes, C. Blundo 
(Universita di Salerno, Italy), A. Cresti (Universita di Roma "La Sapienza", 
Italy), A. De Santis and U. Vaccaro (Universita di Salerno, Italy) 

4:05 - 4:25 Bounds on the share size of multithreshold schemes, 
Wen-ai Jackson, Keith Martin and Christine O'Keefe (Univerity of Adelaide, 
Australia)

4:30 - 4:50 Secret sharing made short, Hugo Krawczyk (IBM T. J. Watson 
Research Center, USA)
_______________________________________________________________________

Tuesday, August 24

Session 6:  Number Theory and Algorithms (Chair: Andrew Odlyzko)

8:30 - 8:50  A subexponential algorithm for discrete logarithms over all 
finite fields, Leonard Adleman and Johnathon DeMarrais (University of Southern 
California, USA)

8:55 - 9:15  An implementation of the general number field sieve,
J. Buchmann, J. Zayer and J. Loho (Universitat des Saarlandes, Germany)

9:20 - 9:40  A factoring experiment, T. Denny (Universitat des Saarlandes, 
Germany), B. Dodson (Lehigh University, USA), A. K. Lenstra (Bellcore, USA) 
and M. S. Manasse (DEC SRC, USA)

9:45 - 10:05 Comparison of three modular reduction functions, 
Antoon Bosselaers, Rene Govaerts and Joos Vandewalle (Katholieke Universiteit 
Leuven, Belgium)
_______________________________________________________________________

10:10 - 10:40  Break
_______________________________________________________________________

Session 7:  Differential Cryptanalysis (Chair: Spyros Magliveras)

10:40 - 11:00  Differential cryptanalysis of Lucifer, Ishai Ben-Aroya and 
Eli Biham (Technion - Israel Institute of Technology, Israel)

11:05 - 11:25  Differential attack on message authentication codes, Kazuo Ohta
(Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corporation, Japan) and Mitsuru Matsui 
(Mitsubishi Electric Corporation, Japan)

11:30 - 11:50  Cryptanalysis of DES in CFB mode, Bart Preneel, Marnix Nuttin 
and Vincent Rijmen (Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Belgium)
_______________________________________________________________________

Wednesday, August 25

Session 8:  Theory (Chair: Russell Impagliazzo)

8:30 - 8:50  A model for entity authentication,
Mihir Bellare (IBM T. J. Watson Research Center, USA) and Phil Rogaway 
(IBM, USA)

8:55 - 9:15  On the existence of statistically hiding bit commitment schemes 
and fail-stop signatures, Ivan Damgard, Torben Pederson
(University of Aarhus, Denmark) and Birgit Pfitzmann (Univeristat Hildesheim, 
Germany)

9:20 - 9:40 Joint encryption and message-efficient secure computation,
Matthew Franklin (Columbia University, USA) and Stuart Haber (Bellcore, USA)

9:45 - 10:05 Cryptographic primitives based on hard learning problems, 
Avrim Blum, Merrick Furst (Carnegie-Mellon University, USA), Michael Kearns 
(AT&T Bell Laboratories, USA) and Richard Lipton (Princeton University, USA)
_______________________________________________________________________

10:10 - 10:40  Break
_______________________________________________________________________

Session 9:  Applications (Chair:  Birgit Pfitzmann)

10:40 - 11:00  Extensions of single-term coins, Niels Ferguson 
(Centrum voor Wiskunde en Informatica, The Netherlands)

11:05 - 11:25, Electronic cash systems based on the representation problem 
in groups of prime order, Stefan Brands (Centrum voor Wiskunde en 
Informatica, The Netherlands)

11:30 - 11:50  Discreet solitary games, Claude Crepeau (Ecole Normale 
Superieure, France) and Joe Kilian (NEC, USA)

_______________________________________________________________________

Session 10:  Authentication Codes (Chair: Doug Stinson)

1:30 - 1:50 Families of hash functions via geometric codes and concatenation,
Jurgen Bierbrauer (Mathematisches Institut der Universitat, Germany),
Thomas Johansson (Lund University, Sweden), Gregory Kabatianskii
(Institute for Problems of Information Transmission, Russia)
and Ben Smeets (Lund University, Sweden)

1:55 - 2:15 On the construction of perfect authentication codes that permit 
arbitration, Thomas Johansson (Lund University, Sweden)

2:20 - 2:40 Codes for interactive authentication, Pete Gemmell 
(UC Berkeley, USA) and Moni Naor (Weizmann Institute of Science, Israel)
_______________________________________________________________________

2:45 - 3:15  Break
_______________________________________________________________________

Session 11:  Hash Functions (Chair: Ivan Damgard)

3:15 - 3:35  Hash functions based on block ciphers: a synthetic approach,
Bart Preneel, Rene Govaerts and Joos Vandewalle (Katholieke Universiteit 
Leuven, Belgium)

3:40 - 4:00 Security of iterated hash functions based on block ciphers, 
Walter Hohl, Xuejia Lai, Thomas Meier and Christian Waldvogel (Swiss Federal
Institute of Technology, Switzerland)
_______________________________________________________________________

Thursday, August 26

Session 12:  Cryptanalysis (Chair: Eli Biham)

8:30 - 8:50 Improved algorithms for the permuted kernel problem,
Jacques Patarin (BULL CP8, France) and Pascal Chauvaud (CNET-France Telecom, 
France)

8:55 - 9:15 On the distribution of characteristics in composite permutations,
Luke O'Connor (University of Queensland, Australia)

9:20 - 9:40 Cryptanalysis on the threshold RSA signature scheme,
Chuan-Ming Li, Tzonelih Hwang and Narn-Yih Lee (National Cheng-Kung 
University, Taiwan)

9:45 - 10:05 Another method for attaining security against adaptively chosen 
ciphertext attacks, Chae Hoon Lim and Pil Joong Lee (Pohang Institute 
of Science and Technology, Korea)
_______________________________________________________________________

10:10 - 10:40  Break
_______________________________________________________________________

Session 13:  Key Distribution (Chair: Tatsuaki Okamoto)

10:40 - 11:00  Interaction in key distribution schemes, Amos Beimel and 
Benny Chor (Technion, Israel)

11:05 - 11:25  New approaches to secret-key exchange, Tom Leighton and 
Silvio Micali (Massachusetts Institute of Technology, USA)

11:30 - 11:50  Broadcast encryption, Amos Fiat (Tel Aviv University, Israel) 
and Moni Naor (Weizmann Institute of Science, Israel)
_______________________________________________________________________



